<div class="heading resPageHeading">


























<h1 >Dean's Scholarly, Research and Creative Activity Award Recipients</h1></div>

<div class="content stackparsys">










				
				<div class="resReference section">

























<div class="restext resText parbase">


























<div class="res-text richtextContent background-hidden" id="e8286d6c-6ff1-4380-8dcd-013b53869e96" >

    <p>The Dean's Scholarly, Research and Creativity Activity Award recognizes individual faculty members on an annual basis for outstanding scholarly, research and creative activities (SRC) achievements and impact on their disciplines during the previous academic year.<br> </p> 
<p>Award recipient(s) will receive a certificate of recognition and a monetary award of $2,000 as a one-time payment (subject to applicable deductions).</p> 
<p><strong>Key criteria: Scholarly, research and creative activity</strong></p>
    





</div>
<script>$(document).ready(function(){addCoursePopover("#e8286d6c-6ff1-4380-8dcd-013b53869e96");});</script></div>

</div>

				

				
				<div class="resText parbase section">


























<div class="res-text richtextContent background-hidden" id="f8d6732d-a967-45a7-87d3-ee90d5873fa8" >

    <h2>2020 recipients</h2>
    





</div>
<script>$(document).ready(function(){addCoursePopover("#f8d6732d-a967-45a7-87d3-ee90d5873fa8");});</script></div>

				

				
				<div class="resText parbase section">


























<div class="res-text richtextContent background-hidden" id="33c8230e-f9b3-4b33-a532-f0c522a08d20" >

    <h3>Natalie Alvarez</h3> 
<h4>School of Performance, Faculty of Communication and Design</h4> 
<p>Dr Natalie Alvarez joined FCAD's School of Performance in 2018 as Associate Professor, bringing with her a distinguished SRC track record. Her SRC productivity is remarkable. In 2018 her book Immersions in Cultural Difference: Tourism, War, Performance was published by the University of Michigan Press. Several other book-length manuscripts, chapters, and articles are in press. Her SSHRC Insight Grant on Scenario Training to Improve Interactions Between Police and Individuals in Mental Crisis led to a substantial research contract for Training Police to Respond to People in Mental Scrisis: a Scenario-based Program and Evaluation Framework.</p> 
<h3>Alagan Anpalagan</h3> 
<h4>Department of Electrical, Computer, and Biomedical Engineering, Faculty of Engineering and Architectural Science</h4> 
<p>Dr. Anpalagan has contributed significantly to engineering education, training, research and innovation. His pioneering work on radio resource management and control technologies in multi-carrier spread spectrum systems has created new research areas and established him as a leader in wireless communication. He has co-authored over 200 journal articles that are highly cited, and co-edited six books including the first handbook on green information and communication systems. As an inspiring mentor, he has trained generations of students who joined academia and industry. For his technical and professional achievements, he has been recognized as Fellow of EIC (Canada) and IET (UK).</p> 
<h3>Stephanie Cassin</h3> 
<h4>Department of Psychology, Faculty of Arts</h4> 
<p>Dr. Stephanie Cassin is a recognized leader in psychosocial obesity care. She has developed close partnerships between her Healthy Eating and Lifestyle (HEAL) lab at Ryerson and several hospital-based obesity programs. Her CIHR-funded program of research focuses on developing and testing psychological interventions for individuals with obesity, and investigating health care innovations that increase treatment accessibility. During the 2018-2019 academic year, Dr. Cassin published a book with Cambridge University Press entitled, Psychological Care in Severe Obesity: A Practical and Integrated Approach. She also published 3 book chapters and 10 peer-reviewed manuscripts, several of which were published in high impact journals.</p> 
<h3>Farhad Ein-Mozaffari</h3> 
<h4>Department of Chemical Engineering, Faculty of Engineering and Architectural Science</h4> 
<p>Farhad Ein-Mozaffari's services to the Chem. Eng. Department, FEAS, Ryerson University, and engineering profession have been exceptional. He has been a member of DHC, DEC, MEIE CLAC, GPC Scholarship, FEAS Award, FPC, Esch Award, MEIE Curriculum, MEIE Admission &amp; Scholarship Committees. He was the technical program co-chair of the XXIX Interamerican Congress of Chemical Engineering and 68th CSChE Conference. He has been a member of the Technical and Scientific Committees of numerous international conferences. Ein-Mozaffari has been the editor, guest editor, and member of the editorial board of many journals including the prestigious journal of Chemical Engineering Research and Design.</p> 
<h3>Konstantinos Georgiou</h3> 
<h4>Department of Mathematics, Faculty of Science</h4> 
<p>Dr. Georgiou deserves the Dean's SRC Activity Award for his contributions in his research expertise, and his training record of HQPs. Dr. Georgiou is a well-recognized scholar in Theoretical Computer Science with more than 60 publications in international peer-reviewed conferences and journals, 10 of which were published in 2019. Only while at Ryerson University, since 2015, he has supervised more than 20 students in various research programs. 4 of his MSc students graduated in 2019. In his career, he has secured $240k in research funding, while he is also prolific in contributing to various SRC activities promoting academic excellence.</p> 
<h3>Anne Harris</h3> 
<h4>School of Occupational and Public Health, Faculty of Community Services</h4> 
<p>Dr. Anne Harris's work on occupational cancer surveillance using the Canadian Census Health and Environment Cohort (CanCHEC) represents a significant achievement for occupational health research in Canada. Along with collaborators at the Occupational Cancer Research Centre (OCRC) and Statistics Canada, the project developed applications of CanCHEC for studies of occupational cancer risk factors, including welding, vibration, firefighting, sedentary work, pesticide and shift work. This work has resulted in 8 peer-reviewed papers, and entailed mentoring of several trainees and junior researchers. This body of work expanding data resource will provide vital context for future research in the field of occupational epidemiology.</p> 
<h3>Janet Koprivnikar</h3> 
<h4>Department of Chemistry and Biology, Faculty of Science</h4> 
<p>Dr. Janet Koprivnikar’s research considers the ecology of infectious diseases in wildlife. Her work takes an interdisciplinary and multi-faceted approach to better understand strategies used by hosts and parasites in defence and maximizing success, respectively, and how these may be affected by environmental perturbations – key issues given that emerging and re-emerging infectious diseases are of major concern for the health of humans, domestic animals, and wildlife. The high impact of this research is underscored by 11 journal articles in the preceding year with students and international collaborators, well as involvement in 9 conference presentations and invited talks.</p> 
<h3>Ali Miri</h3> 
<h4>Department of Computer Science, Faculty of Science</h4> 
<p>Dr. Miri has over 25 years of research experience in security and privacy technologies. He has contributed a stream of innovative solutions to address challenges faced in cybersecurity and computer networks. He is the Director, Information and Computer Security Laboratory (iCaSL), and the Broadband Internet Innovation Center (BIIC), in which he leads a very active research program. He has collaborated with a large number of government and industrial collaborators. He has received over $7M in research funding, supervised 93 HQPs, and has published over 220 manuscripts, books and patents.</p> 
<h3>Tor Oiamo</h3> 
<h4>Department of Geography &amp; Environmental Studies, Faculty of Arts</h4> 
<p>Dr. Tor Oiamo joined the Department of Geography and Environmental Studies at Ryerson University in 2016. Since then, he has established a comprehensive research program to advance knowledge and promote effective policy at the intersection of built environments, health, and wellbeing. Notable achievements include leading the first comprehensive environmental noise study in Toronto; developing a simulation software tool for Health Canada to assess the long-term impacts of urban development on health and sustainability; and most recently, working with a team of researchers to conduct a comprehensive assessment of environmental and population impacts of the King Street Transit Pilot.</p> 
<h3>Fei Song</h3> 
<h4>Human Resources and Organizational Behaviour, Ted Rogers School of Management</h4> 
<p>Dr. Fei Song is the Chair/Professor of HRM/OB in TRSM. She is trained in the field of Organizational Behaviour. Theories and methodologies from social psychology and experimental/behavioural economics have significantly influenced her research. Her research interests include behaviour decision-making, compensation and incentives, risk and uncertainty, social preferences and norms, e.g. cooperation and competition, trust and reciprocity, fairness, group decision-making, and conflict management. She has been the principal investigator on three standard research SSHRC grants and a co-investigator on four other SSHRC standard research grants. She has published in many high-impact management, behavioural /experimental economics, psychology and interdisciplinary journals.</p> 
<h3>Brett Story</h3> 
<h4>School of Image Arts, Faculty of Communication and Design</h4> 
<p>Brett Story is a very prolific artist and scholar, and her SRC output is exemplary of scholarly rigour, aesthetic ingenuity, and commitment to human welfare and climate justice. Her films and scholarship complement each other and garner equal praise. Most notable of her vast SRC output and recognitions over the last year include her appointment as the 2018 Guggenheim Fellow, her first book Prison Land: Mapping Carceral Power across Neoliberal America (University of Minnesota Press), her third feature documentary, The Hottest August, both of which have garnered critical attention and praise, including Variety's Ten Documentary Filmmakers to Watch in 2019.</p> 
<h3>Emily van der Meulen</h3> 
<h4>Department of Criminology, Faculty of Arts</h4> 
<p>Dr. van der Meulen's 2018-2019 SRC activities resulted in significant scholarly and policy impacts in her areas of specialization: sex work and trafficking; surveillance studies; and prison harm reduction. In addition to her on-going research projects, she received three new major research grants (one as PI, two as Co-I) and published three edited books while finishing a fourth. She further published or submitted for publication four journal articles, seven book chapters, and three book reviews in the assessment period. Her expertise was recognized by a range of policymakers, and she was asked to consult various federal and municipal government committees.</p> 
<h3>Lu Zhang</h3> 
<h4>School of Accounting and Finance, Ted Rogers School of Management</h4> 
<p>Dr. Zhang's SRC contribution has been impressive for a finance scholar at this early stage of her career. She has published five papers in peer-reviewed journals. One paper is in a journal ranked A* by the Australian Business Deans Council and two are in journals ranked A by the ABDC. She has presented papers at 8 peer-reviewed conferences and won the Best Finance Paper Award at the Administrative Sciences Association of Canada conferences in 2016 and 2018. She has been successful in obtaining both internal and external research grants including a SSHRC Insight Development Grant as a co-investigator in 2018.</p>
    





